<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Given the changes to DAOC over time, I don't think it's unreasonable to ask that we look at increasing the range, lowering the time, or adding a higher level shout to this line. We'll look into what makes the most sense here. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Good thing. Having played quite a bit with the champion class, shorter recasts and higher ranges will help a lot. A lot. This would be good and welcomed changes.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
The range on the DA seems very low and really limits the utility of this chant. We are looking into changing this (and other song/chant ranges) to make them more viable in RvR. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Good, but it has always, for me, been a given. It will fix a glaring imbalance.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
We're not planning on adding anything specific to this line at this time, with the exception of the above mentioned changes. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Fair enough. We don't want to boost defense, we don't want to boost BS. Okay.<br>
<br>
But answering to demands out of context is not adressing the skald report. The report boils down to one question. It could be summed up in one sentence. this sentence is &quot;Why do skalds have inadequate melee and substandard support ?&quot;. If he isn't answering this question, stating they don't want to add new songs or boost skald survivability is useless. He is perfectly in his rights to say it will be a bad idea to help skald by increasing defense or by adding a new song. Fine. But the general issue should be adressed, and if he is going to rebutt our propositions, might as well make propositions about ways to put back skalds into balance.<br>
<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
This is common for many classes and not specific to the skald. With the recent block/parry changes, players should explore the options of making trade offs to raise parry if they want more in the area of melee defense. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Shrug. I hope he doesn't mean for us to &quot;explore&quot; the enemy frontier alone and groupless because we didn't spec 43 in BS, right <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :o --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/embarassed.gif ALT=":o"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
Seriously, how many logs will be enough to point out there is a problem with skald damage output (compared to their defense and support) with the current specs (high BS and/or high weapons). ? Do we need to decrease our damage still more ?<br>
<br>
And he is just missing the point. This is not &quot;common to many classes&quot;, not to this extent. Only skalds and wardens can spec defensively and only have 1.5x to do this.<br>
Every single melee or hybrid class put the leftover points in parry. Every one. The issue is that there just is more leftovers with 2.0 than 1.5. AND those classes can spec shields. The return on investment for points spent in shield is MUCH better than the points spent in parry.<br>
Having to choose between 50 weapon spec and the best songs are already a choice that skalds are forced to do with their meager skill points allotement, unlike all other melee hybrids. Now are we supposed to spare points who don't have to fix our defensive issues ?<br>
<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Alternate templates are a good thing. We don't want there to be one single &quot;best&quot; template, so we'd look at this as a positive. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Fair enough, but he is missing the point. The point is that this template has been essentially a reaction of skald players caused by 1) The poor scalability and return of investment of the BS spec at the higher (43+) levels (relying on a level 35 and low 40ies spells aven when 50 BS specced ?!?!?) and 2) The poor melee performances of the skald, which triggered the need to spec 50 in weapon to close part of the gap with other melee classes, throwing part of our group supporting, class defining abilities down the drain in the process.<br>
This spec is a testament to the skald imbalances at higher levels, and the general weakness of our BS line, once you have gotten the last taxi spell in the line.<br>
This is what the guy should adress - not congratulating himself about the variety of different and colorfull specs.<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
This is a change that affected all DAs. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Sure, but which other class has no other song or ability to fall back to when playing DA's become inadequate ? Which other class has, by default, the damage add as a class defining ability ?<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
As far as the realm abilities, we'll be reviewing all the underperformers at some point in time, but have no plans to adjust the skald's specifically. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
There is one point I do agree with him : RA's are a general balance issue, not a skald specific issue. I am perfectly comfortable with the idea of not giving FoG priority over the other numerous underpowered RA's.<br>
<br>
However, what frightens me to no ends is that he is wording the whole thing in a way that tends to show the whole thing is not a priority, nor really acknowledged as a big problem by Mythic, and frankly I am appalled. So, there was a desesperate need to destroy the three-realm war because shaman end spell was SO overpowered, yet, they tell us that nothing will be done in the near future to some crap like BoF+faith healing in the realm where overcap AF and ablative songs are available ?<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
This helps skald defense as well. While it makes it more difficult for everyone to attack targets with such defenses, it has no affect regarding skalds and &quot;softer&quot; targets. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Nonsense. This is missing the point.<br>
First, everyone knows and is aware of the fact that one point spent in shield spec give you more than one point spent in parry, and among the defensive triad, parry is the redheaded stepchild. This fix helped shield users first, then heavy parry users (light tanks especially, or some hybrids like LW champs), then, at the very bottom, the low parry hybrids (skalds, wardens ...).<br>
Secondly, like always, skalds don't exist in a vacuum. General, game wide boosts have large scale effects. Throwing a small bone at skalds doesn't cut in when most other classes that go toe to toe with them got much more !<br>
<br>
And what exactly does that comment about soft target means ? Mages are not going to hit back skalds with their staff so that the skald will have an opportunity to parry them ? Are we suddenly able to deflect fireballs with our 2 haders ?<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
We are reworking the resist system and are paying special attention to the effect of the block/parry fix on CC resist rates. <br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Good.<br>
However, skald resist issues predate the last patch ... If the parry/block rework is fixed relative to CC spells, we are just been set back to the exact same status quo as before ...<br>
Other Issues <br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
Nice report. Feel free to keep pushing the defensive issue. But right now, we really want to proceed with caution when evaluating any changes to the classes defense. <br>
----------------------------------------------------------- <br>
<br>
That's just it. This kind of comment mirrors exactly skald's number one concern.<br>
What does he say here ? He says &quot;We have worked hard to rework the game systems, and we are now very happy with the balance we achieved, between attack and defense, and about the duration of battles. We have reached a satisfying state, so we are not going to toy much with individual defenses now&quot;.<br>
The most important part of the TL report - which is not adressed at all in this rebuttal - is that we feel that we were left out, forgotten in a long and thorough balancing process, and now that the balancing is essentially done ... it's more like &quot;though luck guys, we are over and it is too late now, but we'll make sure we won't forget you in future changes&quot;.<br>
This is why the last comment is the most disappointing of them all.<br>
<br>
To sum up, he just dodges the main issues :<br>
- Both melee and support are not up to par. An answer is needed about the definition/role of out class<br>
- Class left out of all of the game and balance changes since day 1<br>
